                LOCAL RESTAURATEUR Joseph Gramaglia Represents <br /><br />Warren at the New Jersey Wine and Food Festival
            </div><br>
            <div class="writer">                
            </div>
            <br /><br />                        
            <p>On May 4-6, more than 1,500 spectators flocked to the New Jersey Wine and Food Festival at Sussex County&rsquo;s Crystal Springs Resort. They came to taste the best in award-winning cuisine, and in the middle of it all they found Joe Gramaglia, owner and Executive Chef at Warren&rsquo;s own Saly Gs Restaurant and Tavern!</p>
            <p>&ldquo;This was a tremendous opportunity for me as a chef, and as someone who never had formal culinary training,&rdquo; Joe says. &ldquo;I got to work alongside some of the best chefs in the world. What an inspiration to watch them work &ndash; it really reinforces the idea that as chefs, we&rsquo;re always learning and there are always new things to try.&rdquo;</p>
            <p>Joe spent the weekend in a non-stop cooking frenzy, preparing over 1,000 plates in all. The highlight, he says, was the May 5<sup>th</sup> Garden State Culinary Throw down &ndash; a &ldquo;Chopped&rdquo; style competition that saw Joe take second place, missing the top spot by only one vote!</p>
            <p>For the throw down, he was given five ingredients: stinging nettles, ramps, peanut potatoes, mixed baby carrots, and mushrooms. He was then tasked with coming up with an on-the-spot delicacy. Joe&rsquo;s creation was a Fancy Toast with nettle and walnut pesto, charred ramps, peanut potato and onion hash, mushroom and truffle ricotta and crispy carrots.</p>
            <p>He got the chance to flex his culinary muscle even more at the 7 p.m. &ldquo;Grand Tasting&rdquo; main event that evening, when he paid tribute to his family&rsquo;s Italian heritage with a Piedmontese Beef Tartare (the Piedmont being a breed of cattle that originated in the Piedmont region of northern Italy). The entr&eacute;e featured a lemon caviar with blackened sea salt, parmesan, and organic egg yolk served in the tartare over crostini.</p>
            <p>Throughout the weekend, the chefs were mentored by Chefs Daniel Boulud and Thomas Keller - &ldquo;two of the best in the world,&rdquo; Joe says. All food for the events was donated by Fossil Farms of Boonton.</p>
